Body:
## What works

Define helper functions at the top of your shader (outside `void fragment()`) and they're emitted into the GLSL alongside main(). Built-in references inside the helper body — `UV`, `TIME`, `SCREEN_UV`, `MODULATE`, `TEXTURE_PIXEL_SIZE`, `SCREEN_PIXEL_SIZE`, `TEXTURE`, `FRAGCOORD` — are auto-rewritten to the underlying uniform / varying / GL keyword, so the helper sees them naturally:

```glsl
shader_type canvas_item;

vec3 stripes(float spacing) {
    return vec3(step(0.5, fract(UV.y * spacing)));
}

void fragment() {
    COLOR = vec4(stripes(10.0), 1.0);
}
```

The translator emits `UV` inside `stripes()` as `v_uv` (the varying), so the helper resolves the per-fragment UV correctly without `stripes()` needing to take `uv` as a parameter.

Helpers can call other helpers and the substitution chains naturally:

```glsl
float ramp(vec2 uv) { return uv.x * uv.y; }
float corners() { return ramp(UV); }    // UV → v_uv
```

## The one gotcha: COLOR

COLOR is the lone built-in that DOESN'T substitute in helpers. It can't — it's per-fragment read-write state, and GLSL ES 3.00 has no module-scope mutable to hang it on. So COLOR lives as a local variable in `main()`'s scope; helpers that need to read or write it must take it as a parameter:

```glsl
// Helper that READS COLOR — take it by value
float luma(vec4 c) {
    return dot(c.rgb, vec3(0.299, 0.587, 0.114));
}

// Helper that WRITES COLOR — take it as inout
void tint_red(inout vec4 c) {
    c.rgb *= vec3(1.5, 0.5, 0.5);
}

void fragment() {
    COLOR = texture(TEXTURE, UV);
    float l = luma(COLOR);
    tint_red(COLOR);
}
```

The inout-vec4 pattern is idiomatic GLSL anyway and reads cleanly at the call site.

## Why this works the way it does

Godot's runtime injects canvas_item built-ins into `fragment()`'s scope as locals. A helper function called from `fragment()` doesn't get those injections — same constraint we hit in the live preview. Two paths Bleepforge could have taken:

1. **Auto-rewrite helper signatures + call sites** to pass built-ins as parameters. Smart but invasive; needs a real recursive-descent parser to track which helpers reference which built-ins and what calls what. ~10× the parser code for one quality-of-life feature.
2. **Substitute built-in references inside helper bodies** to the underlying uniform / varying expressions. Tiny code change (just a different substitution table per scope), works for every built-in whose backing form is module-scope-visible.

We took path 2. The translator's [HELPER_SUBSTITUTION_MAP](https://github.com/ymoraviadev-droid/bleepforge) maps each non-COLOR built-in to its replacement expression — `TIME → u_time`, `UV → v_uv`, `SCREEN_PIXEL_SIZE → (1.0 / u_resolution)`, etc. Helper bodies pass through this table on emit; fragment() bodies don't (they keep the existing local-built-in references).

## Vertex / light functions

The parser also recognizes `void vertex(...)` and `void light(...)` as entry points, but they're **dropped from the emitted GLSL** — they belong to vertex / per-light pipelines the live preview doesn't run. The editor still shows them with full syntax highlighting; they just don't ride into the live shader. If you need to preview a shader that depends on a custom vertex stage, render in Godot. Spatial / particles / sky / fog shader types are also out of v1 scope — see [the translator subset reference](/help/shaders/translator-subset).

## Edge: shadowing a built-in name with a local

GDShader / GLSL both let you shadow a built-in identifier with a local variable. If your fragment body declares `vec2 UV = ...;`, you're redeclaring main()'s local — that's a GLSL error you'd hit in Godot too. Inside a helper, `vec2 UV = ...;` would be valid because the helper-body substitution only fires on standalone identifier references, not on declarations. Tested but uncommon — if you ever feel the urge to name a local `UV`, rename it first.
